[~hspencer], it has always been the case with Euca that when you create an autoscaling group and want to associate with a load balancer the load balancer must exist first. =I found an [AWS doc|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AutoScaling/latest/DeveloperGuide/US_SetUpASLBApp.html] stating the same order of ops. An existing load balancer is [also called out|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AutoScaling/latest/DeveloperGuide/as-register-lbs-with-asg.html] as part of the prerequisites when creating a scaling group associated with a load balancer

{quote}
Elastic Load Balancing uses load balancers to monitor traffic and handle requests that come through the Internet. To use Elastic Load Balancing with your Auto Scaling group, you first have to create a load balancer and then you need to register your Auto Scaling group with the load balancer. 
{quote}

As far as the other scenario (deleted then re-created associated LB) I believe association with a load balancer is done at instance launch time.  So it would make sense that that when a new load balancer is created existing instances of the autoscaling group would not register to it, only subsequently launched instances would. This may be a compatibility issue but it is not a regression.
